                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d427">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1905-10-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 27, 1905</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 213.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge with thanks the
                    receipt of your letter No. 340, of the 25th October, regarding the Newfoundland
                    fishery question, and to assure you that I highly appreciate the spirit in which
                    it was written.</p>
                <p>It will be in no way disagreeable to me that you should take the course you
                    propose with regard to my letter of the 20th October, and I will with your
                    permission communicate to the Newfoundland government, for the information of
                    their people on the treaty coast, the substance of your reply.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">H. M. Durand.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
